    "created_at": "2017-02-23T01:20:19Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-02-23T01:20:19Z",
    "body": "Hi @hariprasadiit !\r\n\r\nThanks for the `app.dock.hide()` tip!\r\n\r\nAnd now that we know that works, I have a theory as to why:\r\nWhen an app has a dock icon, the app itself can be focussed. For example, when you click the app's dock icon, the name of the app shows up in the menu bar next to `File Edit View` etc. The same thing happens when you click in the app's window. When an app has no dock icon, you can click on the app's window and yet some other application will still have the menubar. So if it was `Finder` and you open and focus your app, the menubar still shows `Finder`.\r\n\r\nTLDR: macOS (OS X) running apps show in the dock; hiding dock icon = background app thus app windows no longer linked to menubar and (more importantly) spaces."
  }
